<TEXT>
exxon and alaskas top environmentalist 
squabbled over the pace of the oil spill cleanup monday as skimmers 
in the gulf of alaska sought refuge from rough seas for the second 
day in a row 
hatchery owners on prince william sound meanwhile announced 
that 24 million salmon fry have been released into the sound where 
they must swim through seas hit by the spill 
the salmon had to be released sunday and monday in conjunction 
with the bloom of plankton in the sound to enhance their rate of 
survival 
we really have no choice but to release them now said 
heather mccarty a spokeswoman for the nonprofit prince william 
sound aquaculture association which owns three hatcheries in the 
sound 
it is unclear what will happen to the fry as they migrate to the 
open sea if they encounter oil mccarty said 
as cleanup work continued in the sound gale warnings and seas 
swelling to 18 feet kept aircraft on the ground and skimmers close 
to shore monday said coordinators of the militarys role in the 
cleanup 
exxon however called a news conference to announce that the 
cleanup was ahead of the pace calculated in the oil companys 
federally approved plan which figures the cleanup will be done by 
sept 15 
kt koonce exxon usas vice president for exploration and 
production said 70 percent of the 101 milliongallon spill had 
evaporated dissipated or been recovered the company said 18 
gallons had been recovered an estimated 12 million gallons 
remains afloat 
the oil spilled march 24 from the exxon valdez a fully loaded 
tanker that ran aground on bligh reef as it steered from the valdez 
terminal through prince william sound 
dennis kelso commissioner of alaskas despartment of 
environmental conservation questioned exxons claim and said the 
oil companys efforts remain inadequate 
i would look carefully at the figure and not take it at face 
value said kelso adding that the estimate was based on exxons 
computer models and could be off by as much as 50 percent 
what i want to see is some results he said after exxons 
news conference 
while the rough seas kicked oil onto beaches that had previously 
been spared mondays weather also broke up oil and increased the 
likelihood that more crude will be carried to the open seas of the 
gulf of alaska 
we see this storm as a good thing said karen gleason a 
spokeswoman for the national oceanic and atmospheric administration 
fishermen from homer and other maritime communities south of 
anchorage have sewn absorbent material into nets and are picking up 
oil in much the same way they might be gathering herring this time 
of year 
a cleanup priority has been set for beaches where seals come out 
with their pups each summer thousands of sea birds and hundreds of 
otters already have been found dead 
state officials have canceled or postponed herring black cod 
and shrimp harvests in the sound and closed a portion of the 
kodiak herring fishing grounds 
fisheries officials in seattle were expected to decide wednesday 
whether to cancel the may 1516 halibut season heavy oil has been 
reported around the barren islands at the mouth of cook inlet where 
many large boats congregate for the 24hour open season 
in los angeles meanwhile vice president dan quayle warned oil 
companies not to use the nations worst oil spill as an excuse to 
raise gasoline prices 
if they are it is going to be a very difficult situation for 
them quayle who plans a firsthand look at the cleanup next 
month said in los angeles 
allegations have been made that a temporary shortage of oil 
caused by the spill was used a pretext for gas price hikes 
quayle made his comments after meeting with former president 
reagan and his wife nancy in los angeles as he left on a trip to 
australia and southeast asia he is scheduled to visit prince 
william sound on his way back may 4 
quayle said he would tour the area and collect information for 
president bush 
</TEXT>
