a national transportation safety board staff 
report recommends several changes in air traffic control operations 
over southern california as a result of incidents of airplanes 
flying too close together a board source says 
the board was taking up the report at its public meeting today 
after its investigation into the loss of standard separation 
between a british airways jumbo jet and an american airlines 
jetliner on feb 13 over westminster calif 
the report recommends increases in staff and training at the 
coast terminal radar approach control facility in orange county 
calif some improvements and expansion of the facility itself and 
several technical changes the source said speaking on condition 
of anonymity 
the investigation of the british airwaysamerican incident was 
expanded to cover seven other operational errors over the past year 
at the facility just south of los angeles the traffic control 
operation handles about half a million flights a year in the skies 
between los angeles and san diego which is one of the busiest 
flight areas in the country outside major airport control zones 
the board meeting on southern california air traffic control 
problems comes two days after two reports of airliners nearly 
colliding in the new york area 
a twa jumbo jet coming in from london and a commuter plane flew 
about 100 feet apart as they approached kennedy international 
airport on sunday and 45 minutes later a pan am boeing 727 en 
