in the new indictment 
but it appeared that walsh decided not to pursue that 
armsresupply allegation because it was fraught with the same 
secrecy concerns that forced him to drop similar charges against 
north 
earlier this year walsh dropped charges that north conspired 
with others to divert 15 million in usiran armssale profits to 
the nicaraguan rebels when the government refused to release secret 
documents the trial judge ruled were needed for norths defense 
a federal court jury in washington is deliberating on 12 related 
charges against north including allegations he lied to congress 
about the irancontra affair 
legal observers have considered the fernandez case even more 
laden with secrecy problems because his lawyers are expected to 
seek court approval to disclose details of his cia activities in 
central america where he used the alias tomas castillo 
walsh avoided those issues by obtaining a narrow indictment 
charging that fernandez lied when he denied he helped set up the 
airstrip in northern costa rica for the resupply operation and said 
he did not know that north was involved in the effort 
fernandez is also accused of lying to the cia by stating that 
the airstrip was built by the costa rican government to train 
pilots for a possible nicaraguan invasion of costa rica 
each of four charges in the indictment carries a maximum 
fiveyear sentence and a 250000 fine upon conviction 
the original fivecount indictment brought in washington was 
dismissed oct 19 after a judge ruled the charges should have been 
