a union leader acquitted of 
charges he tried to take control of an impoverished black township 
says he will rebuild the community organizations that authorities 
alleged were subversive 
a judge on monday acquitted moses mayekiso head of the national 
union of metalworkers and four other black activists of subversion 
charges ad said the boycotts they organized were legal protests of 
poor living conditions 
happy supporters carried mayekiso on their shoulders from the 
supreme court to the nearby central methodist church after the 
verdict police ordered the crowd to stop singing and chanting and 
told reporters to leave 
