<TEXT>
the supreme court by a 63 vote today tossed 
out a dispute over the federal governments power to ban newspapers 
from publishing lists of winners in privately run lotteries 
the justices ruled that a controversy from minnesota has become 
moot because the government no longer intends to enforce the ban 
we conclude that there is no longer any live controversy on 
the issue of whether the challenged statute is constitutional as 
it applies to prize lists and that this appeal is moot the 
court said in an unsigned opinion 
justices byron r white and thurgood marshall cast dissenting 
votes but did not explain why 
justice john paul stevens in a brief dissenting opinion said 
the court should have reversed not merely set aside a federal 
judges ruling that had upheld the publishing ban 
the minnesota newspaper association originally challenged a 
postal law that bars newspapers from carrying advertisements and 
prize lists 
postal laws currently prohibit use of the mails to disseminate 
information about any lottery not run by a state since nearly all 
newspapers rely on the mail for at least a portion of their 
distribution the postal laws apply to them 
but after the justices agreed last october to study the case 
congress enacted a new law to take effect in may 1990 dropping 
the ban on advertising for private lotteries the newspaper 
association and the government agreed to drop that part of the case 
government lawyers then told the justices that the existing ban 
on publishing prize winners will not be enforced 
the dispute had focused on lotteries and other gaming such as 
bingo and raffles sponsored by nonprofit charitable 
organizations and others 
lawyers for the minnesota newspapers said the revenue 
generated by charitable gaming is very substantial in minnesota 
alone it appears to exceed 200 million per year 
us district judge paul a magnuson upheld the ban on lottery 
advertising even though he acknowledged that the ads are a 
constitutionally protected form of commercial speech the newspaper 
association appealed 
the judge however ruled that newspapers cannot be barred from 
running lists of private lottery winners unless such lists are 
found in advertisements the government had appealed that part of 
his ruling 
the case is frank vs minnesota newspaper association 871956 
</TEXT>
