<TEXT>
a unanimous supreme court today upheld a 1986 
federal law imposing safety user fees on pipeline companies 
that transport natural gas and hazardous liquids 
the court reversed the ruling of a federal magistrate in 
oklahoma that the law that allows the secretary of transportation 
to impose user fees to pay for pipeline safety programs 
unconstitutionally gives the executive branch too much of congress 
power to impose taxes 
justice sandra day oconnor wrote for the court that the law 
clearly is not an unconstitutional delegation of the taxing power 
by congress to the executive branch 
the userfee system is being used to pay for pipeline safety 
programs costing about 85 million to 93 million a year 
the law had been challenged by midamerica pipeline co a 
transporter of hazardous liquids it has been assessed a 53000 
fee in 1986 by the secretary of transportation 
us magistrate john l wagner in tulsa okla ruled in 1987 
that the assessments are taxes and therefore the law improperly 
gives the transportation secretary the power to set tax rates 
in her opinion today however oconnor said we need not 
concern ourselves whether the pipeline safety user fees are 
really taxes 
assuming they are she said we hold that the delegation of 
discretionary authority under congress taxing power is subject to 
no constitutional scrutiny greater than that we have applied to 
other nondelegation challenges 
had the court upheld the magistrates ruling its decision could 
have affected a broad range of federal fees and taxes 
as examples government lawyers cited congressional 
authorization for the nuclear regulatory commission to assess 
nuclear power plant operators for licensing and inspection and for 
the federal energy regulatory commission to impose fees to pay the 
cost of its various programs 
the assessments may be based on the amount of pipeline miles a 
company operates the quantity of natural gas or liquid and how far 
it is shipped or the gross revenue of the company 
the case is skinner vs midamerican pipeline co 872098 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

