sales of existing homes dropped 43 percent in 
march the third straight monthly decline as rising mortgage 
interest rates made more inroads into the housing market a real 
estate trade group said tuesday 
the national association of realtors said sales of existing 
singlefamily homes dropped to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 
333 million units in march the slowest pace since february 1988 
sales had dropped 2 percent in february and 94 percent in 
january 
the march figures were the latest in a series of reports that 
indicate rising interest rates are slowing the economy and taking a 
toll on home sales and residential construction last week the 
government reported that construction of new homes and apartments 
declined 54 percent in march the second straight monthly decline 
because housing usually slows down in advance of other sectors 
of the economy the weak performance has heightened fears that a 
recession could come later this year or in early 1990 the federal 
reserve board for a year has been pushing up interest rates as part 
of a campaign to slow the economy and keep inflation in check 
this is another piece of evidence that things are softening 
and that high interest rates do make a difference maury harris 
chief economist for painewebber inc said of the latest housing 
report 
fixedrate home mortgages averaged between 1086 percent and 
1122 percent in march up a full percentage point from a year 
earlier according to the federal home loan mortgage corp 
ira gribin president of the realtors said the higher rates are 
having their biggest impact on firsttime home buyers he said they 
are the first to leave the market and the last who are able to 
get back in 
with fewer sales last month to firsttime buyers the median 
price of existing homes sold rose 1200 to 93100 meaning half 
the homes sold for more and half for less 
what we are seeing is definitely a tradeup market said 
john a tuccillo chief economist for the realtors people still 
in the market are those with the incomes to withstand higher 
monthly mortgage payments resulting from higher interest rates 
