<TEXT>
the federal national mortgage association said 
tuesday it is beginning a pilot project aimed at providing up to 
100 million for creative home mortgages for the elderly 
the program is aimed at making housing more available and 
affordable for the elderly with mortgages that reduce housing costs 
or allow senior citizens to supplement their income by taking 
advantage of the equity in their current homes 
vice president david p riordan said fannie mae would encourage 
lenders to offer these mortgages to the elderly and commit to 
buying up to 100 million in the mortgages on the secondary market 
fannie mae which is congressionally chartered is the nations 
largest investor in home mortgages 
the program will provide mortgages for accessory apartments 
within a singlefamily home which an elderly person could then 
rent for extra income temporary housing units built on a family 
members property homes shared by a senior citizen and one or more 
other adults and the sale of a home by an elderly person to a 
family member or investor who then rents it back to the seller 
david o maxwell fannie mae chairman said it will alter 
underwriting standards as part of the project permitting lower 
down payments on certain types of mortgages and including net 
rental income as part of a borrowers qualifying income 
riordan said the loans are offered now on a sporadic basis if at 
all and that fannie mae hopes to encourage the availablility of 
the loans and determine which are most successful he said the 100 
million represents a significant commitment to elderly housing 
to qualify a person must be 62 or older 
</TEXT>
