thousands of workers at the countrys 
central bank went on strike tuesday and a bank spokesman said 
foreign debt payments and other financial transactions were 
jeopardized 
the central bank strike broke out as other government bank 
employees and workers at private banks entered the sixth day of a 
separate strike 
murilo murca de carvalho a central bank spokesman said by 
telephone from brasilia that a significant number of the banks 
7000 workers around the country stopped work 
nanci toffoli a spokeswoman for the central bank workers union 
in sao paulo said at least 5000 workers across the country joined 
the strike 
carvalho said the strike was already causing difficulties and 
could eventually force our operations to come to a standstill 
the central bank brazils equivalent of the us federal 
reserve controls shortterm market investments the domestic money 
supply government bond trading foreign exchange operations and 
investments of brazils hard currency reserves in the international 
financial market 
the strike could affect brazils foreign debt payments 
depending on how long it lasts carvalho said without elaborating 
brazil the largest nation in latin america is the third 
worlds largest debtor nation it has a foreign debt of 115 
billion 
central bank workers are federal employees who earn salaries 
averaging 680 a month they are demanding a 150 percent pay 
increase to keep pace with annual inflation of more than 1000 
percent 
