a number of atlanta banks and thrift institutions 
said tuesday they would cooperate with a justice department 
investigation of possible racial discrimination in the areas 
mortgage lending industry 
im sure the justice department will find a good level of 
cooperation among atlantas financial institutions said dallas 
lee a spokesman for citizens and southern national bank 
the washington post reported tuesday that the justice department 
wants to see loan records covering the past five years as part of 
an investigation of the 64 banks and savings and loan associations 
in the metropolitan atlanta area 
the newspaper said the agencys civil rights division in 
letters that began arriving monday gave the institutions official 
notice that they are under civil investigation the letters signed 
by acting assistant attorney general james p turner asked the 
institutions to make the records available voluntarily it said 
lee and others said the banks have taken significant steps in 
the past year to do away with discrimination in mortgage lending 
we are surprised that atlanta was the city the justice 
department picked for its investigation considering all the 
activities that have taken place in the last year said bo 
spalding director of communications for bank south i wouldnt 
be surprised if after all of this atlanta has a rather exemplary 
record of minority lending 
we dont feel we have discriminated overtly said james j 
wallace of fulton federal savings bank i dont think there is a 
single instance of outright discrimination by any of the larger 
institutions 
the post said the case is the broadest inquiry into socalled 
redlining since the government settled a suit against the national 
real estate appraisal associations in the late 1970s 
redlining which is prohibited by federal law is the refusal to 
lend on the basis of race or other factors unrelated to credit 
worthiness 
the investigation was prompted by articles beginning last may in 
the atlanta journal and the atlanta constitution that disclosed a 
segregated mortgage system in which banks and thrifts made few 
loans in black areas even in upperincome black areas and often 
made mortgage services less accessible to black home buyers 
atlantas largest banks responded to the articles by pooling 77 
million for lowinterest mortgages primarily in black 
neighborhoods a few of the largest banks also changed some 
policies such as increasing contacts with black real estate 
agents many smaller institutions reported no changes 
the justice inquiry going beyond information available to the 
newspaper seeks records of actual loan applications and credit 
reports on mortgage applicants the post said 
