<TEXT>
americans think its more important for 
newspapers to cover religion than sports a new national study 
finds but people are a bit more likely to read sports stories 
indications also turned up that increasing religious coverage 
likely wont do much to boost circulation since 
religioninterested readers already make up the bulk of readership 
the religious and religioninterested readers are already 
there says the project director steward m hoover of temple 
university in philadelphia religiosity and newspaper readership 
are statistically associated 
preliminary findings of the study described as the first 
comprehensive research on press coverage of religion and interest 
in it were presented recently to the religious public relations 
council convention in washington 
concerning the relative news importance of nine special fields 
religion was found to rank about in the middle below education 
health and business but above sports food personal advice 
entertainment and art 
when people were asked to rate their likelihood of actually 
reading about the topics religion also ranked in the middle but 
below sports ahead of sports again were health education and 
business 
the study sponsored by religious news service under a grant 
from the lilly endowment included two national gallup polls of 
1100 samples each plus indepth interviews in a variety of local 
congregations 
contrary to assumptions that people are primarily interested in 
local religion stories we discovered great expressions of 
interest in national and international religion stories said 
judy weidman rns editordirector 
in ranking the importance of types of religion news the polls 
gave first place to social and ethical positions and 
pronouncements by major faith groups such as on abortion 
nuclear policy and the economy 
while local church news and announcements ranked second all 
the other highlyrated categories were national and international 
in scope rather than locally or individualistically oriented 
hoover said 
these included in this order ethical and social issues 
the role of religion in foreign or international politics the 
role of religion in american politics and national religious 
issues and controversies 
hoover said the findings undermined triedand true 
assumptions that readers want stories of faith and 
inspiration or opinion commentary about religion these rated low 
in appeal 
the findings confirmed what we have been hearing in our 
localcongregational interviews hoover said people think of 
religion in national and even global terms they know it is a 
dimension of other news they clearly want that dimension to be 
covered well 
seventyone percent of those polled called themselves daily 
readers and 81 percent said religion is important in their lives 
of these considering religion important a higher proportion 80 
percent are daily readers 
more than half of the total sample 522 percent said it was 
important for newspapers to cover religion as well as other kinds 
of news 
asked how well the press covers the various specialties sports 
got the most excellent scores followed by business food and 
entertainment but a rather poor job is seen in religious coverage 
it ranked seventh 
the sad truth is that many of this countrys almost 1700 
daily newspapers either ignore the religion story or amuptate it at 
the county line ms weidman said 
a still incomplete part of the study involves interviews with 
eight newspapers regarded as covering religion well three already 
have been visited the los angeles times the tennessean in 
nashville and st petersburg fla times 
what these newspaper executive believe in common is that the 
religion story is central to interpreting life in their communities 
and american culture in general ms weidman said 
debunking an old claim that a news professional needs to be 
religious to give a fair shake to religion she quotes teresa 
wasson city editor of the tennessean as saying 
im an atheist myself but i have great respect for religion 
as a motivational force in peoples livesreligion is simply not 
important to many reporters or editors personally and thus they 
dont understand how personally important it is to readers 
i think they dont understand the richness of coverage 
available in religion its not just socials and churchy things 
religion is very rich turf in news value and many editors dont 
know that 
</TEXT>
