<TEXT>
teeming shantytowns sprawl across the hills 
surrounding caracas in venezuela and more and more as economic 
conditions worsen they are becoming breeding grounds for social 
unrest an associated press correspondent visited one recently and 
filed this report one of a series on the economic social and 
political turbulence that has turned south america into a continent 
in crisis 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
maria zurbaran ruiz her commomlaw 
husband and their eight children live in a tinroofed threeroom 
shack called a rancho on the slope of a hill overlooking caracas 
they consider themselves fortunate 
he has a job making bricks 10 to 12 hours a day 100 miles away 
in valencia for roughly the equivalent of 25 a week 
the good life for her is being able to feed her the children 
corn bread and coffee sometimes with milk for breakfast black 
beans and spaghetti for lunch and again for dinner and meat on 
saturdays when her husband luis antonio zambrano is home 
but maria zurbaran ruiz who is 48 years old said things wont 
be that way much longer 
she was talking about the recent turn of events in venezuela 
price increases that set off rioting down on the streets of caracas 
feb 27march 2 leaving 276 people dead and about 1000 injured 
there are several bad years ahead she said nothing will 
be easy anymore 
some of those who went down into the streets to protest loot 
and burn were from marias slum rancholandia 
it is the kind of place in south america where riots and 
sometimes revolutions are born 
maria said she tells her children to prepare themselves for hard 
times she has 14 in all 7 to 33 years old but just eight still 
live with her 
i was blessed with 20 children she said but my triplets 
and another three died in the 60s from disentery 
millions like maria and her family live in ranchos on the hills 
around venezuelan cities 
maria and luis antonio arent as poor as most of them nor as 
better off as some of them 
she stays at home while he goes off to work mondays through 
thursdays in valencia before leaving valencia for home on 
weekends he stops at a slaughterhouse and with part of his pay 
buys a kilo of meat 22 pounds 
with luis antonio at home for the weekend saturday is the 
feast day maria said everyone gets a piece of meat mixed with 
a lot of boiled potatos so that everybody is full for the rest of 
the day maybe it wont be every saturday anymore 
she was thinking again about the price increases and the riots 
the price increases were part of a government austerity program 
intended to halt the downward economic spiral venezuela has been in 
since the collapse of oil prices a few years ago 
the program called for the lifting of subsidies that kept prices 
low for the poor at the same time the bolivar the local 
currency was allowed to float for the first time in decades and 
prices for unsubsidized goods and services also rose 
the government of president carlos andres perez said it had no 
alternative but it did not expect people to pour out of the 
ranchos as they did 
they came by the thousands in caracas at least 50 percent of 
the population of 4 million lives in ranchos 
sociologists and politicians analyzed the sudden swarm of 
protest as the revenge of the havenots against the rich 
maria said she had no part of it 
here we are all honest people the malandros criminals 
came from up the hill she said gesturing with her left thumb 
there wasnt much hill left before the top and it was hard to 
determine where the malandros could have come from 
all that can be seen from marias rancho are myriads of other 
ranchos crammed over the hills like a waving ocean of corrugated 
metal 
full employment is rare in the ranchos many people are 
completely jobless others are underemployed and still others make 
a living as street vendors 
maria considers herself lucky because luis antonio has the 
brickmaking job in valencia where he stays with his mother during 
the work week to save bus fare back and forth every day 
maria adds about 400 bolivars 13 to the weekly budget by 
sewing pants on a neighbors machine and sweeping a nearby school 
twice a week 
but electricity is free in rancholandia people simply hook 
into the power lines and water comes from a public line not far 
from marias rancho 
ranchos began sprouting in venezuelan cities only during the 
last 30 years while the nation was establishing itself one of the 
most stable democracies in latin america 
before that the dictatorial governments that ruled most of the 
time since independence from spain in 1811 barred the poor from 
building shacks in the cities 
they were kept in rural areas and the few who made it into 
caracas were constantly harassed by authorities 
but after the dictatorship of marco perez jimenez collapsed in 
1958 the poor were allowed in from the countryside and as the 
nations oil economy burgeoned they flocked to the cities for jobs 
caracas and other cities soon were overwhelmed by a new socialwing 
decade when venezuela began to swell with oil money 
the couple built a sturdier one of adobe and concrete blocks a bit 
further down the hill 
now we do have space she said pointing to the narrow 
partly walled space where she cooks and does the laundry at 
midday it is the only cool place in her rancho heat in the rest 
of the shack soars over 100 degrees 
this is the best we could get she said but i think my 
children will get something even better 
</TEXT>
