<TEXT>
an unprecedented show on art deco 
brings together some of the best decorative works of the 1920s from 
12 european nations to redefine the whimsical elitist style of the 
rich and powerful 
in all 274 pieces from fine jewelry and glassware to massive 
bulky dressers are on show until the end of may at the beauxarts 
palace itself an art deco gem to mark its 60th anniversary this 
year 
the art deco in europe exhibit aims to shed new light on the 
muchabused concept of the movement by highlighting work from as 
far apart as sweden czechoslovakia and italy the style is an 
eclectic ode to superficial prettiness for the rich who failed or 
refused to face the harsh social realities of the 1920s 
the difference between art deco and other styles of its age is 
often very thin said exhibit organizer marc lambrechts explaining 
why art deco has often been confused with and used as an amalgam 
of everything from stark modernism to flamboyant rococo the 
kaleidoscope of forms and shapes at the beauxarts palace might 
still leave many visitors lost for a uniform vision of art deco 
but then art deco loved to quote from foreign and bygone 
styles from the japanese and chinese cultures from rococo and 
classicism much in the same way that postmodernism does today 
lambrechts said only the social idea behind the pieces 
constituted the art deco style there is no unity of form no 
real style he said only a common attitude of snobbery and 
elitism among art deco artists and buyers 
through his show lambrechts paints a picture of a gilded cage 
in which a spoiled european elite sought to shield itself from the 
revolutionary changes that swept society early this century it did 
so by cultivating an art that had no meaning other than to please 
the eye 
in contrast the contemporary modernism of le corbusier and 
walter gropius thrived on the new technologies and social 
developments art deco shunned through its devotion to function and 
lack of ornament it gave shape to many of worlds modern cities 
in almost all the capitals of europe the high bourgeoisie 
tried to compensate the threat to its power with a refined culture 
while the new rich wanted to create an identity by purely showing 
off lambrechts said 
in return art deco was dismissed as kitschy and tasteless for 
many decades but in recent years it has found a new following as 
evidenced by the fact that over 2000 people a day visited 
lambrechts show which opened march 3 at victor hortas beauxarts 
palace in the center of brussels 
france and britain have long claimed to be the cradle of art 
deco but lambrechts show breaks new ground there it shows strong 
contributions from across europe many of them on display for the 
first time outside their home countries 
the exhibit is not as complete as lambrechts would have liked 
as much art deco was destroyed in west germany by the nazis who 
considered it decadent 
still culled from 101 museums and private collections from 
around europe it shows a lot of previously undiscovered beauty 
among the best arts and crafts this century has produced 
lambrechts said 
what all the pieces have in common is a sense of luxury expert 
finishing and craftmanship leafgold silver gems china 
delicate woods no costs were spared to produce a unique work of 
art deco 
while modernists employed concrete and steel to allow function 
to prevail over style art deco only wanted to impress with its 
flashy materials and ornaments 
and impress they did 
dutchman hendrik van den eynde was lavish enough in his use of 
silver but his 1918 urn flanked by four statuettes shows some of 
the restraint other works at the show dearly lack 
at the other end of the spectrum austrian anny schroeder 
outrages with loud clashing colors and seemingly irrelevant 
drawings of hunters and exotic deer on her 1919 mask 
and nowhere is craftmanship and use of rich materials more 
evident than in the art deco jewelry of the maison van cleef and 
arpels 
its 1927 vanity brooch of gold enamel christal emerald 
rubies and diamonds wrought by master hands is one of the 
highlights of the exibit 
after spending some decades in relative obscurity dealers are 
also quickly reevaluating art deco some small tables have been 
sold for close to 1 million and prices for all objects are rising 
constantly 
times have changed said lambrechts today art deco is 
even more expensive than french art of the 18th century 
</TEXT>
