<TEXT>
from gone with the wind to a southern 
family writers have addressed the south with much sound and fury 
but vs naipaul has used his acute eye to furnish some fresh 
insights in a turn in the south 
naipaul a trinidadian of indian descent who has lived in 
england for nearly four decades spent six months traveling through 
the south studying race relations religion the romance with the 
past and its wary concessions to progress 
a turn in the south knopf 1895 takes the reader from 
greensboro nc where naipaul begins his sojourn through 
atlanta charleston sc tallahassee fla tuskegee ala 
jackson miss nashville tenn and back to north carolina at 
chapel hill he shows us confederate monuments and catfish ponds a 
selfproclaimed redneck and a nashville songwriter fundamentalist 
preachers and a futuristic nissan assembly plant 
the oxfordeducated naipaul is the author of 19 other books 
eight of them nonfiction works such as this one in which he 
exhaustively explores a locale they are much too complex to be 
considered mere travel books he is best known for his caustic 
pictorials of third world countries in both his nonfiction 
india a wounded civilization the loss of el dorado 
the middle passage and his novels a bend in the river 
guerrillas in a free state 
for example among the believers his controversial 1981 
account of the islamic faith in iran pakistan and indonesia 
probably would elicit a death threat from the ayatollah khomeini if 
it were issued today 
one of the pleasures of reading a turn in the south is 
experiencing the southern united states through the eyes of a world 
traveler the land was flat like the pampas of argentina or the 
llanos of venezuela naipaul writes of greensboro 
interviewing naipaul about the writing of this book is another 
experience altogether he detests interviews submits to them only 
on the insistence of his publisher and endures them with a pained 
air and mostly terse responses 
asked in a recent interview for example to explain what kind 
of advance work he does before setting out on a destination he 
said curtly i dont i dont do any research 
when the interviewer points out that in his book he says he has 
obtained letters of introduction that this sounds like advance 
preparation and asks him how he decides whom to contact naipaul 
responded that is always difficult 
when pressed to elaborate he would add only it varies from 
place to place it is one of the difficulties of the traveling 
business 
asked if he read any southern authors beforehand such as 
william faulkner or eudora welty whom he interviewed in a turn 
in the south he snapped thats fatal i always refuse to 
read in advance 
after a pause he added i always try to see what ive found 
im a fairly welleducated wellread person and ive spent all my 
life writing and i have a rough idea of the history of places i 
like to go and see what i find and move from there i dont want to 
be reacting against other peoples views 
in a turn in the south naipaul writes that this will be his 
last travel theme book why abandon a format that has served him so 
well 
i felt it at the time i felt i was getting on said 
naipaul who is 56 but what happened was i was so energized by 
it researching the book so excited so delighted i was so 
delighted by the method i had stumbled on in my middle 50s i found 
it so true and interesting and i so marveled that i hadnt 
alighted on it before i found that at the end of it quite a bit of 
energy remaining or generated and i thought i should do a 
little more before my chest absolutely packs up on me naipaul 
suffers from asthma 
the methodology to which he referred is to interview a wide 
range of people and to let them do the talking rather than his old 
habit of spending a long period in a given place quietly observing 
and analyzing which he now says gives a more prejudiced account 
naipaul seems unaware that the new method he has stumbled upon 
is that used daily by journalists 
naipauls next trip will be to india where he has traveled 
extensively but he didnt know if a book would come of it he said 
that because of his poor health he views every book as his last 
</TEXT>
