<TEXT>
nearly a century after chauncey wing 
invented a simple device to stick mailing labels onto newspapers 
his greatgrandson is turning out almost identical wing mailers 
handcrafted on turnofthecentury lathes for modern newspapers 
times change but the wing mailer just goes along said 
donald wing the latest in the long line of yankee tinkerers and 
inventors to preside over the little brick mill in this 
northwestern massachusetts town 
he estimated that 3000 to 4000 of the devices are being used 
by newspapers ranging from large metropolitan dailies such as the 
boston globe and the hartford courant to hometown weeklies 
many bigger papers use it to back up their computerized 
systems the fancy electronics are only as good as the people who 
operate and fix them and they still have to get out the papers when 
the power goes off said wing and for the smaller papers it 
can be a lot more economical 
the device which feeds a strip of mailing labels through a glue 
well and then cuts and affixes the labels onto the newspapers with 
a pull of the thumb was invented in 1894 
the familyowned company still occasionally gets back for 
repairs mailers made 50 and 60 years ago said paul sevrens who 
manages the fiveemployee factory the only difference between 
these older models and the ones made today is that after the 1920s 
the mailers were made of aluminum instead of brass today the 
mailers cost about 215 
even the cherrywood handles that chancey wing and james a 
horton editor of the greenfield gazette and courier chose for the 
mailer when grover cleveland was in the white house remain still 
turned on a footdriven lathe 
there would be no purpose to changing said wing 45 our 
customers are familiar with it as it is and we dont care about 
being modern 
in its one concession to the computer age the company last year 
unveiled a new model without a glue well to handle preglued 
computer labels but otherwise the 2pound machine that has 
outlasted all its competitors is a handheld anachronism in the 
heavily computerized newspaper industry 
the factorys only pause was during world war ii when henry 
wing donalds father halted production to mill parts for 
topsecret radar research 
the companys sales including supplies totaled 250000 last 
year wing said 
to step into the plant near the family home is to walk into 
the 19th century 
most of the machines were made here and some even predate the 
mailer said wing a turnofthecentury fivehorsepower 
electric motor in the basement powers the more than two dozen gear 
cutters taps dies and presses through an intricate arrangement of 
leather belts and pulleys that whir overhead 
the electric bill for the whole plant is about 20 a month 
said sevrens wife peggy the office manager 
its hard to find people with the skill and inclination to work 
often by eye on the old machines sevrens said but his 
fascination came early 
i grew up in the neighborhood and did odd jobs for henry 
wing said the young machinist he was interested in everything 
and always working on all sorts of things tinkering i just 
thought he was kind of a neat guy 
richard haskins 78 who retired and returned twice because i 
dont have a place where i can have a hobby said he wouldnt 
want to work on a modern computerized milling machine 
theres a nature to man that can be lost he said a 
machine can make a standard socket but when youre finished 
theres nothing of toolmaker in it 
</TEXT>
