<TEXT>
the cost of wages salaries and benefits to 
the nations employers rose 12 percent in the first quarter of 
1989 with increases in benefits costs again outpacing pay gains 
the labor department reported today 
the employment cost index report showed that for the 12 months 
ended march 31 the cost of wages salaries and benefits rose 48 
percent down slightly from the 5 percent average for calendar 1988 
but up significantly from the 1987 jump of 36 percent 
the index measures changes in an employers costs for all forms 
of compensation principally wages and salaries and employerpaid 
benefits such as health insurance it is closely watched as a 
barometer of inflation particularly in the past year as analysts 
have speculated that the tight labor market would drive up 
compensation costs because of increased competition for workers 
analysts disagreed over whether the figures signaled a faster 
pace of wage gains and therefore increased inflationary pressure on 
the economy 
the numbers are reasonably favorable and there are no signs of 
wage acceleration said michael evans president of a washington 
economic forecasting firm except for the one sore spot of rising 
health care costs i think the figures show wage gains continue 
to be stable and no signs of rapid acceleration 
but economist roger brinner at data resources inc in lexington 
mass said the report indicated labor costs are creeping up 
he predicted the annual rate of employer cost increases which 
would be 45 percent if the firstquarter numbers held throughout 
the year would climb to 5 percent and possibly to 55 percent over 
the next year 
with unemployment down to almost 5 percent workers feel that 
they can ask for their normal share which is the sum of inflation 
and productivity brinner said in a telephone interview 
inflation on usproduced goods is about 45 percent and 
productivity gains have been in the 1 percent to 15 percent range 
the rate of employer costs could slow however if unemployment 
rises brinner predicted that the civilian jobless rate 50 
percent last month would edge up in the next quarter and reach 55 
percent or slightly higher by years end 
the 12 percent increase in the index for the first quarter 
compared with 10 percent in the final quarter of 1988 and 14 
percent from the first quarter of last year the labor department 
reported 
the increase for the first three months of 1989 was attributed 
to a 11 percent jump in wage and salary costs and a 18 percent 
rise in employers costs for benefits escalating health care costs 
have been the largest factor in the rising costs of benefits 
for the year ended march 31 the government said wages and 
salaries for workers in private industry rose 42 percent while the 
cost of benefits rose 51 percent 
employer costs for workers in service industries rose 15 
percent in the first quarter up from 12 percent in the final 
three months of 1988 and the 13 percent gain reported in the first 
quarter of 1988 
in the goodsproducing industries employer costs rose 10 
percent for the quarter up from 08 percent in the final quarter 
of 1988 but down from the 18 percent jump reported for the first 
quarter of last year 
