gov terry branstad asked federal 
officials tuesday to help soften the effects of a spring drought by 
activating emergency feed programs and allowing cattle to graze on 
fragile acres normally held out of production 
our recent scattered rains may have helped in some areas but 
certainly they were not dustbusters by any means branstad said 
branstad said up to 40 percent of the states pasture has been 
destroyed by dry weather this spring cattlemen said farmers 
already have started selling off their herds and may speed up the 
liquidation within the next two weeks if they do not get help 
it is appropriate to take action early the governor said 
these are difficult times for our cattle producers 
branstad asked us department of agriculture officials to 
activate emergency programs to give farmers financial aid in buying 
feed and to allow grazing on highly erodable acres taken out of 
production 
gene wiese of manning presidentelect of the iowa cattlemens 
association said farmers are facing a bleak future because the 
prime months for growing pasture are april and may 
this is normally when we have lush growth in our pastures 
he said in many areas of our state thats just not happening 
before any decision can be made on the assistance requests a 
countybycounty survey must be completed something branstad said 
could take two weeks 
programs the governor requested include 
allowing grazing on conservation reserve program acres land 
for which farmers receive annual payments to hold out of 
production that grazing would be allowed initially for 30 days 
but could be extended if dry weather continues 
activating an emergency feed program giving up to 5 cents per 
pound for assistance to farmers purchasing feed 
activating another feed program where farmers can purchase 
feed owned by the government for 75 percent of its loan value 
they do not require any outlay of cash branstad said 
adding he was confident federal officials would approve the 
request were not asking for anything thats out of line or that 
will run into a wall of resistance 
government officials however have warned that farmers should 
not expect a massive federal bailout similar to one approved last 
year due to the drought that gripped much of the midwest 
but wiese said cattle farmers need some signal that government 
will help or many will begin to sell herds 
we need some assurances to carry on he said 
branstad said the immediate threat was to livestock producers 
we wont really know the impact on crops until much later 
branstad said he said he would seek drought aid for other farmers 
if the drought continues and worsens throughout the year 
