<TEXT>
cable industry leaders are teaming up to 
encourage use of cable tv programming in the classroom including a 
new daily news program that could rival a similar show for schools 
from whittle communications lp cable industry and education 
sources said tuesday 
the effort which is expected to be announced at a news 
conference wednesday in washington dc comes on the heels of 
whittles completion of a 25show test in school classrooms of its 
commerciallysponsored news program channel one 
the cable group includes some of the nations biggest cable 
programmers and operators led by turner broadcasting system inc 
which operates cable news network and reportedly will produce the 
daily news show 
the atlantabased turner broadcasting scheduled a news 
conference for wednesday at the national press club to announce a 
new venture to benefit american schools 
also scheduled to attend were top officials of the cable 
networks arts amp entertainment cspan and the discovery channel 
along with cable operators telecommunications inc continental 
cablevision inc and jones intercable 
turner spokesmen refused to elaborate on the topic of the news 
conference and the other participants either declined comment or 
failed to return calls 
but one education industry source requesting anonymity said he 
had been told turner will disclose plans for a daily news show for 
use in schools 
in addition to turners news show the other networks either 
would create new programming or more heavily promote the 
availability of their existing shows for use in schools cable 
industry sources said 
it will be a mix of programming of current events and some 
cultural and educational type programming a nice mix said one 
cable executive familiar with the groups plans discussing it 
provided he was not identified 
it was not clear whether the programming would contain 
commercials as whittles channel one service does or whether the 
cable group would donate equipment on the scale of that envisioned 
in the channel one project 
whittle launched channel one a daily 12minute news show with 
two minutes of paid advertising in six test schools march 6 the 
schools were each given about 50000 in video equipment tv 
monitors and satellite dishes in exchange for agreeing to run the 
program every school day 
the cable industry effort was being viewed in part as a way for 
the cable industry to show it is being a good citizen at a time 
when calls have arisen for greater regulation of the industry 
it also reflects an effort to protect cables turf against the 
entry of an outsider the knoxville tennbased whittle 
turner has been involved for two years in a joint venture with 
the national school boards association called news access that 
has made available cnns the week in review program and a 
detailed classroom guide with suggestions on how to use portions of 
the show in schools 
the news access program which is being used in about 220 
schools relies on schools to use their own equipment to record and 
show the program 
cspan the discovery channel and the arts amp entertainment each 
have their own arrangements for sharing programs and course guides 
with schools 
but none of those efforts has drawn the attention that whittles 
channel one test did 
whittle is reviewing the results of the sevenweek test ended 
last week and hopes to decide by midsummer whether to make the 
program available nationally in the fall of 1990 
