<TEXT>
traders surveyed by one of the countrys largest 
brokerage firms say they have not changed the way they do business 
despite the governments investigation of activities at the chicago 
board of trade and the chicago mercantile exchange 
eighty percent of more than 1100 private speculators who 
responded to the lindwaldock amp co survey said disclosure of the 
fbi probe on jan 23 had not affected their trading methods the 
brokerage firm reported tuesday 
sixtynine percent said they believed trading pits at the 
nations commodity futures exchanges operate honestly and 
efficiently but 63 percent thought the exchanges could do a 
better job of policing themselves 
we wanted to know how our customers felt about the industry 
said barry lind president of lindwaldock a chicagobased futures 
discount brokerage 
with futures trading in the headlines he said we thought it 
would be a good time to get information 
the federal probe of suspected trading fraud at the board of 
trade and the merc the worlds two largest futures exchanges has 
not yet produced any official charges or indictments 
of those who said they had changed the way they traded 12 
people or 1 percent said they had stopped trading as a result 
of the investigation others said they changed the type of orders 
they placed or said they were trading less than before 
the survey was of active clients as of march the brokerage said 
