<TEXT>
exxon corp said tuesday it has been hit with 31 
lawsuits and 1300 claims ranging from 500 to 4 million in 
connection with last months alaskan oil spill and expects further 
suits as well as government fines 
at a meeting of securities analysts top executives of the 
nations biggest oil company said exxon already had paid 400000 
to settle smaller claims brought mainly by fishermen and cannery 
workers whose jobs were disrupted because of the march 24 spill 
that fouled hundreds of miles of coastline 
exxon executives declined to put a dollar value on the existing 
lawsuits or the claims 
exxon chairman lawrence c rawl who has been criticized for 
staying out of sight in the crucial days following the disaster 
said that in retrospect he would have responded differently 
however he said he did not understand the public anger against the 
company especially because it had accepted the blame and 
apologized for the spill and was cleaning it up 
im angry with myself rawl said its not really clear to 
me as to why everyone is so angry once we get past the point of 
admitting it was our ship that went on the rocks 
exxon president lee r raymond said all but two of the lawsuits 
were class actions against the company all but one were filed in 
alaska state and federal courts he said with the remaining suit 
filed in california 
raymond said exxon has four separate insurance policies totaling 
5998 million in cleanup and liability coverage including a 400 
million policy that would pay off even in cases of company 
negligence but raymond said the various policies cant necessarily 
be added together 
raymond said the insurance would cover most if not all of the 
cleanup costs and that therefore its impossible for us at this 
point to make any provision for our earnings for any reserves 
on monday exxon announced that it had charged 30 million 
against firstquarter earnings for expenses associated with the 
salvage and repair of the broken tanker but not for the cleanup 
itself 
raymond also said the company probably was subject to fines but 
did not yet know what fines various government agencies might 
impose 
rawl said the company did not anticipate any punitive damages 
due to the spill in which an exxon tanker ran onto a reef and 
spewed more than 11 million gallons of crude oil into prince 
william sound 
there obviously was no intent on our part to put a very 
expensive ship on bligh reef to put expensive oil in the water and 
then a very very very expensive cleanup rawl said 
in response to criticism that exxon did not have enough people 
working on the cleanup rawl said exxon would increase the number 
to about 4000 by next month he also reiterated his optimism that 
despite concerns by alaska officials the major part of the spill 
would be cleaned up by september 
exxon told a news conference monday that the cleanup was ahead 
of the pace calculated in the oil companys federallyapproved 
plan which estimates cleanup completion by sept 15 
when questioned about the impact of a possible boycott against 
exxon rawl said that with anticipated tight supplies and high 
demand during the summer season its hard to see this summer how 
we wouldnt be able to sell all the gasoline we can make 
a number of consumer activists have called for a boycott of 
exxon to punish the company for what they claim is its poor 
response to the disaster and alleged negligence leading to the 
spill 
the boycott will damage the dealers who are independent 
business people rawl said 
rawl said the spill hasnt changed exxons outlook or spending 
plans he also declined to specify when the company would declare 
its next dividend which generally is issued quarterly 
as to changing exxons tarnished image he said its pretty 
clear theres a better way to do that job but we havent had time 
to sort that out were going to have to do a hell of a lot better 
job than we have done 
