<TEXT>
employees caring for elderly relatives often 
experience jobrelated stress and increased absenteeism and 
corporate america can expect even more of these problems as the 
population ages a private study released tuesday found 
if elder care is a problem now and it is we had better 
find good humane answers soon if we dont the future will 
turn into a nightmare for millions of us said e james morton 
chairman of john hancock financial services which conducted the 
study along with fortune magazine 
the study was based on responses from 370 senior executives and 
369 people in the general employee population 
it found that six out of 10 senior executives were aware of 
specific workrelated problems with elder caregiving employees 
fortyfive percent of the executive respondents noticed employee 
stress 38 percent unscheduled days off 37 percent late arrivals 
and early departures 32 percent aboveaverage use of the 
telephone and 30 percent absenteeism the survey said 
those in service companies were more likely than industrial 
companies to report having these problems the survey said 
a vast majority of the employees questioned 70 percent 
admitted that taking care of elderly relatives or friends 
interfered with job performance 
fiftyone percent of them said they felt increased tension on 
the job as a result of their responsibilities the survey said 
fortyfour percent also admitted to increased use of the telephone 
and that same percentage had to take more time off for emergencies 
the survey said 
fourteen percent said their productivity was affected it said 
the survey found that women were more likely to shoulder 
responsibilities for caring for the elderly and take a socalled 
daughter track approach in which their careers are slowed as 
they juggle work and parental care 
executives havent been immune to these problems either the 
survey said that half of them are personally responsible for an 
elderly person now or have been in the past two years and one out 
of every two executives reports being concerned about maintaining 
job performance 
caregivers spend on average 13 hours a week tending to the 
elderly usually a parent with responsibilties ranging from 
providing transportation and companionship to performing simple 
household chores 
about a quarter of all fulltime employees in the united states 
reportedly provide some care for the elderly who represent roughly 
12 percent of the us population that figure is likely to 
increase over the years with the elderly population expected to 
nearly double by the year 2030 and as nursing home care expenses 
rise 
with this rapid increase in the elderly population and with 
caring for the elderly being a family responsibility we must 
expect growing pressure on the workplace said leslie 
gainesross a research director for fortune this dual 
responsibilty will be overwhelming both emotionally and 
financially 
this dual responsibility will affect business bottom line 
resulting from lost employee production and higher healthcare 
expenses 
few companies though offer programs to deal with this problem 
other than providing things like unpaid leaves of absence or 
personal days to their employees ms gainesross noted 
it might be beneficial for corporations to educate managers as 
to the enormity of elder care responsibilities she said 
understanding the problem goes a long way to coping with it and 
resolving it 
the surveys margin of error was plus or minus 5 percentage 
points 
</TEXT>
