<TEXT>
a private analyst said tuesday that poor 
moisture reserves in much of the nations midsection have already 
taken a modest bite out of this years crop yields and that the 
situation could worsen if the rains arent abundant this spring 
economist john schnittker head of schnittker associates a 
washingtonbased agricultural consulting firm said that the 1988 
drought remains the leading force in world agriculture at 
least until more is known about this years crops of wheat and corn 
both schnittker and the agriculture department project huge 
declines in world and us inventories as a result of last years 
droughtshriveled yields in north america 
by july 1 he said the global grain inventory going into the 
new 198990 season will be down to a 61day supply compared with 
an 87day reserve last summer that will be the smallest reserve 
since the early 1970s when global grain stocks were drawn down to 
a 57day supply 
speaking to a meeting of the national association of 
agricultural journalists schnittker said the supply situation puts 
the united states sort of on the razors edge because of the 
uncertainties about 1989 crop conditions 
although many areas are dramatically improved from last years 
summer drought parts of the great plains and corn belt are still 
woefully dry even in some areas that have moderate surface 
moisture the reserves deep in the subsoil are scant 
and if we do have a second adverse cropgrowing season the 
effect will be substantially larger in the commodities markets and 
in the consumer food retail markets than they have been the past 
year schnittker said 
the reduced 1988 harvests forced up market prices for the major 
crops as it became apparent that the us granary would be 
partially emptied 
schnittker said he finds himself disagreeing quite a lot 
with usdas chief meteorologist norton strommen who told the farm 
writers earlier that he was still optimistic that crop conditions 
will improve and that nationally the united states can have a 
productive year 
strommen and others maintain the fate of the us winter wheat 
crop will not be known for another month or so and that farmers 
still have not planted spring wheat or made much of a dent in 
planting corn 
if i seem a little on the optimistic side it may be that im 
looking at changes that have occurred and the improvements that 
have taken place since the fall of 1988 and the real harshness of 
the 1988 drought strommen said 
acknowledging there are pockets of drought problems still around 
kansas for example where about 75 percent of the winter wheat 
is reported in very poor or poor condition strommen said many 
other sections of the country have had good moisture last year in 
recent months 
when you put all of the big parts together the overall 
outlook for the country is much improved over what it was last 
year strommen said but we are still deeply concerned about 
the pockets and the problems we have in the western great plains 
and the central part of the corn belt 
schnittker said strommen may turn out to be right but it 
seems to me with the extreme subsoil drought concentrated on 
the central corn belt at the moment that it is prudent for private 
forecasters at least to reduce the probable corn yield a little 
bit 
already he said the moisture problems have shaved this years 
average corn yield if all had been normal the yield trend pointed 
to an average of about 120 bushels per acre but schnittker says he 
thinks 115 bushels are more likely 
that would mean a 1989 corn harvest of about 754 billion 
bushels up from 51 billion bushels estimated for 1988 the usda 
currently estimates last years corn harvest at 492 billion 
bushels but has not projected the 1989 crop 
based on april 25 conditions schnittker forecast this years 
total us wheat harvest at 215 billion bushels about 300 million 
bushels less than the output would be if moisture conditions had 
been normal last years wheat harvest was 181 billion bushels 
