<TEXT>
texaco incs profit soared in the first quarter helped by a 
substantial onetime gain from a major restructuring while rising 
crude prices took a toll on most of the nations other large oil 
companies 
mobil corp reported a 22 percent drop in firstquarter earnings 
compared with the same 1988 period while chevron corps profit 
was down 52 percent and occidental petroleum corps fell 41 
percent shell oil co said its profit slipped 7 percent 
texaco said its profit rose more than fivefold to 15 billion 
or 591 a share from 270 million or 111 a share in the first 
quarter of 1988 
texacos firstquarter results included a net restructuring gain 
of 12 billion or 487 a share the company said 
the nations thirdlargest oil company based in white plains 
ny said it realized 13 billion from the sale of texaco canada 
inc after special charges texaco sold its 78 percent stake in the 
canadian subsidiary to exxon corp in january 
texacos revenue for the first three months of the year totaled 
96 billion up 10 percent from 87 billion in the yearago 
quarter 
despite the gains texacos refining and marketing margins were 
hurt by rising crude oil prices in the absence of a corresponding 
increase in product prices the company said however domestic 
exploration and production results benefited from the higher crude 
prices 
mobil based in new york said its firstquarter earnings fell 
to 429 million or 104 a share from 549 million or 133 a 
share in the comparable 1988 quarter 
revenue totaled 14 billion up slightly from 139 billion in 
last years first quarter 
mobil chairman allen e murray attributed the profit decline to 
volatile crude prices which resulted in a 44 percent drop in the 
companys refining and marketing earnings exploration and 
production earnings were off 22 percent however murray predicted 
that a continued rise in product prices including gasoline could 
produce a turnaround in the second quarter 
san franciscobased chevron reported net income of 313 million 
or 91 cents a share down from 653 million or 191 a share in 
the same period last year revenue totaled 77 billion up from 
75 billion 
chevron chairman ken derr noted that crude oil in november cost 
about 13 a barrel but had risen to 20 a barrel by the end of the 
quarter he said prices at the gas pump did not increase fast 
enough to make up the difference 
occidental reported aftertax profit of 67 million or 24 cents 
a share down sharply from 113 million or 52 cents a share sales 
were 51 billion compared with 45 billion in 1988s first 
quarter 
the los angelesbased company said the 1988 results included a 
net gain of 53 million from the issuance and sale of stock by one 
of its subsidiaries 
occidental said the firstquarter results reflected the early 
paydown of 9 million in debt as well as a lower crude oil sales 
volume stemming from the july 1988 north sea piper platform 
accident 
shell a unit of the royal dutchshell group of companies based 
in england and the netherlands said its us consolidated earnings 
in the quarter were 362 million down 7 percent from 390 million 
in the yearearlier period revenue totaled 52 billion up from 
51 billion last year 
sun cos earnings for the first quarter increased 35 percent 
the radnor pabased company said citing improved results in 
domestic refining and marketing 
suns profits totaled 81 million or 76 cents a share compared 
with 60 million or 57 cents per share in 1988s first quarter 
revenue totaled 265 billion up from 239 billion 
excluding 16 million in earnings reported in the first quarter 
of 1988 from domestic oil and gas operations that have since been 
spun off to stockholders as sun exploration and production co 
suns earnings increased 84 percent 
